{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "While disinformation is often used interchangeably with misinformation in the literature, the latter presents a slightly different nuance.",
    "According to the EDAP, \"misinformation is false or misleading content shared without harmful intent though the effects can be still harmful, e.g.",
    "when people share false information with friends and family in good faith\".",
    "The nuance between the two terms lies in the intention for dissemination, which may be challenging to determine a priori.",
    "Establishing a legal definition of disinformation also posed a challenge in the context of the Digital Services Act (DSA), as policymakers aimed to ensure the term was comprehensive enough to distinguish it without over-regulating the information ecosystem [168]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Establishing a legal definition of disinformation also posed a challenge in the context of the Digital Services Act (DSA), as policymakers aimed to ensure the term was comprehensive enough to distinguish it without over-regulating the information ecosystem [168]."
  ]
}